    title: "1. Variables & types",
    intro: "Python is dynamically typed. A variable is not a labeled box that holds a value; it is a name bound to an object that lives elsewhere in memory. Writing `x = 7` creates the integer object `7` (or reuses an existing cached one) and points the name `x` at it. Reassigning `x = \"hello\"` does not mutate the integer; it rebinds the name to a brand-new string object. That mental model matters the moment you start passing things to functions, because every argument is a fresh binding to the same underlying object.\n\nThe four scalar types you reach for daily are `int`, `float`, `str`, and `bool`. Integers are arbitrary precision in Python, so `2 ** 1000` works without overflow. Floats are IEEE 754 doubles, with the usual floating-point surprises (`0.1 + 0.2 != 0.3`). Strings are immutable sequences of Unicode codepoints, not raw bytes. Booleans are a subclass of `int`, which is why `True + True` evaluates to `2` and why you can use a boolean directly as an array index.\n\nThe `type(x)` built-in returns the runtime class of any object and is the fastest way to confirm what you are holding when things go sideways. `isinstance(x, int)` is the correct membership check because it respects subclassing — handy for booleans masquerading as integers.\n\nF-strings, written `f\"value: {x}\"`, are the modern way to interpolate. They evaluate the expression inside the braces at runtime, support format specs like `f\"{pi:.2f}\"`, and as of Python 3.8 the `=` debug syntax `f\"{x=}\"` prints both the expression and its value. Older idioms like `\"value: \" + str(x)` or `%`-formatting still work but read worse.\n\nA few subtle gotchas worth internalizing early. Mixing `int` and `str` with `+` raises `TypeError`; wrap with `str()` or use an f-string. Comparing values with `is` checks object identity, not equality — it only happens to work for small interned integers and short strings by accident. And while Python does not require type declarations, optional type hints (`x: int = 7`) feed editors and tools like `mypy` without changing runtime behaviour. Lean on them once your code grows past a single file.",
