    id: "p2",
    title: "2. Conditionals",
    intro: "Control flow in Python is built on `if`, `elif`, and `else`. Each branch test is an expression that gets coerced to a boolean by Python's truthiness rules, then the first branch whose test is truthy runs. Comparison operators (`==`, `!=`, `<`, `>`, `<=`, `>=`) yield booleans directly, and you combine them with the keyword operators `and`, `or`, and `not` — not the C-style `&&`, `||`, `!`, which Python does not have. Reaching for `&` and `|` here is a common bug; those are bitwise operators with different precedence and they will silently misbehave on integers.\n\nTruthiness is the rule that makes `if items:` mean \"if the list has anything in it.\" Empty containers, the number `0`, the empty string, and `None` are all falsy; everything else is truthy. Lean on this instead of writing `if len(items) > 0`. The one exception is when you genuinely need to distinguish `None` from an empty value — there, use the explicit `if x is None` check.\n\nIndentation is part of the syntax, not a style choice. Every line inside a branch must indent by the same amount; PEP 8 says four spaces. Mixing tabs and spaces in the same block raises `IndentationError`. Forgetting the trailing colon on `if`, `elif`, or `else` raises `SyntaxError` — a daily papercut for newcomers.\n\nFor the common pattern of picking one of two values, the conditional expression `value = a if cond else b` reads like English and avoids a four-line `if/else`. Chain comparisons work the way mathematicians write them: `0 <= x < 10` is exactly what it looks like, not `(0 <= x) < 10`. Short-circuit evaluation means `a and b` skips evaluating `b` if `a` is falsy, and `a or b` skips `b` if `a` is truthy — useful for guarding against `None` (`name = user and user.name`).\n\nFinally, Python 3.10 introduced structural pattern matching with `match`/`case` for richer branching on shapes — useful for ASTs, JSON dispatch, or replacing a long `elif` chain that destructures tuples. It is not a replacement for everyday `if`; it shines when you are picking branches by type or shape rather than by a single value.",
