    id: "p4",
    title: "4. Lists",
    intro: "A list is Python's general-purpose ordered, mutable, heterogeneous collection. Internally it is a contiguous array of pointers to objects, which gives O(1) indexing and amortized O(1) append. Insertion or removal anywhere except the tail is O(n) because every following element has to shift; if you find yourself doing that in a hot loop, reach for `collections.deque` instead, which gives O(1) appends and pops on both ends.\n\nIndexing uses `lst[i]`, with negative indices counting from the end (`lst[-1]` is the last element). Slicing — `lst[start:stop:step]` — returns a new list and never raises `IndexError` for out-of-range bounds; it just clips. `lst[:]` is the idiomatic shallow copy. Be aware shallow means the outer list is new but its elements are still shared references, which matters for lists of lists; for true independence use `copy.deepcopy`.\n\nThe everyday mutating methods: `append(x)` adds one element, `extend(iter)` adds many (faster and clearer than `+=` for that purpose), `insert(i, x)` places at index `i`, `pop()` removes and returns the last element, `pop(i)` removes by index, `remove(x)` removes the first matching value, and `sort()` sorts in place. The non-mutating siblings return new lists: `sorted(lst)`, `reversed(lst)` (returns an iterator), and slicing.\n\nList comprehensions — `[expr for x in iter if cond]` — are the Pythonic way to build a new list by transforming or filtering another. They are roughly equivalent to a `for` loop with `append`, but they read closer to math and are noticeably faster because the bytecode skips per-iteration attribute lookups. Reach for them whenever you are mapping or filtering; reach for a real loop when each iteration does more than one expression's worth of work.\n\nThe single biggest gotcha is aliasing. Writing `b = a` does not copy; both names point at the same list, and mutating one mutates the other. Use `a[:]`, `list(a)`, or `copy.copy(a)` when you need an independent shallow copy. Equality is value-based (`==`) — never compare contents with `is`, which checks object identity and will give you the wrong answer except by coincidence.",
    code: "nums = [3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2, 6]\nprint(nums[0], nums[-1])  # first, last\nprint(sorted(nums))\nsquares = [n*n for n in nums]\nprint(squares)",
