    title: "1. Hello + types",
    intro: "Every C++ program enters at `int main()`. The compiler links your translation unit, runs `main`, and uses the integer it returns as the exit code — `0` for success, anything else for failure. Pull in features through headers: `#include <iostream>` for console I/O, `#include <string>` for `std::string`. Headers are not modules — they are textual includes that paste their contents at the include point, which is why include order can occasionally matter and why heavy headers slow compiles dramatically. `using namespace std;` drops the `std::` prefix; convenient in small files and contest code, dangerous at file scope in production headers because it pollutes every translation unit that includes them and can cause silent ambiguity with user-defined names. Daily-driver scalar types: `int` (at least 16 bits, usually 32 on every modern platform), `long long` (at least 64), `double` (IEEE 754 64-bit float), `bool`, `char`. When a count can plausibly exceed two billion — array sizes, prefix sums, timestamps, byte offsets — pick `long long` and stop worrying. Floating-point is not real arithmetic: `0.1 + 0.2` is not `0.3`, comparisons need an epsilon, and accumulating millions of small values drifts because each step rounds. Reach for `double` by default and `long double` only when a numerical method needs the extra precision. `std::string` owns its character buffer, grows automatically, and works with `+`, `==`, `<`, and the stream `<<` operator. The C-string `const char*` literal `\"hello\"` decays to a pointer; concatenating two of those with `+` does not compile, because pointer arithmetic is the wrong operation. Output uses `std::cout` chained with `<<`. The `endl` manipulator writes `'\\n'` and flushes the buffer; in tight I/O loops `'\\n'` alone is faster because it skips the flush. Variables are statically typed and initialized when you write `int x = 7;`. Uninitialized locals hold garbage and reading them is undefined behaviour — always initialize at the declaration, using `int x = 0;` or `int x{};` for value-initialization. `auto` lets the compiler deduce the type from the initializer, which is invaluable once template-heavy code shows up. Forgetting to `return 0;` from `main` is harmless — the standard inserts it for you — but being explicit is the convention. Compile with `-Wall -Wextra -Wpedantic` from day one; the warnings catch a real percentage of beginner bugs before they ship, and treating them as errors with `-Werror` is the right default for new projects.",
