    id: "cpp2",
    title: "2. Control flow",
    intro: "Control flow in C++ looks familiar — `if`, `else if`, `else`, `while`, `for`, `do…while`, `switch` — but the language packs a few sharp edges into the syntax that bite when you treat it like Python or JavaScript. `if` takes a `bool`; any integer or pointer converts implicitly, so `if (ptr)` and `if (n)` are idiomatic null/zero checks. Each branch is a single statement unless wrapped in braces, and forgetting the braces is how dangling-else bugs sneak in when someone adds a second line under an `if` and forgets to add braces. Always brace, even one-liners. The ternary `cond ? a : b` is an expression, not a statement — useful inside initializations: `int label = age >= 18 ? 1 : 0;`. Both arms must produce the same type, or one must convert to the other through the usual arithmetic conversions. The comparison operators `==`, `!=`, `<`, `<=`, `>`, `>=` work on primitives and on `std::string` (the standard library overloads them member-wise to compare contents). They do not work the way you want on raw C strings: `const char* a = \"hi\"; const char* b = \"hi\"; a == b` compares pointers, not contents, and the result is implementation-defined depending on whether the compiler pools identical string literals. Use `std::string` or `strcmp`. Logical operators `&&`, `||`, `!` short-circuit, so `if (p && p->next)` safely guards a null deref. Bitwise `&`, `|`, `^` do not short-circuit and operate on bits — easy to confuse with the logical pair and a real source of subtle bugs. The dreaded `if (x = 5)` compiles, assigns 5 to x, and is always true; `-Wall` warns about this and saves the day. `switch` jumps to a matching `case` label and keeps executing — fall-through is the default — so insert `break;` after every case unless you genuinely want to fall through, in which case `[[fallthrough]];` (C++17) documents intent and silences the warning. C++17 also added an initializer-statement to `if` and `switch`: `if (auto it = m.find(k); it != m.end()) { use(it); }` scopes `it` to the `if`/`else` block, the cleanest way to look something up and react to whether you found it without leaking the iterator afterwards. Loops have the same three flavours as C — `while`, `do…while`, the three-clause `for`. The range-based for — `for (auto& x : container)` — is the modern default; reach for the index form when you need the index itself, need to skip elements, or need to iterate in reverse.",
