    title: "4. unordered_map",
    intro: "`std::unordered_map<K, V>` is the hash table — average O(1) insert, lookup, and erase, but worst-case O(n) if the hash collapses or an adversarial input collides every key into the same bucket. Its tree-based cousin `std::map<K, V>` keeps keys sorted and offers O(log n) operations with predictable worst-case performance; pick `map` when iteration order matters, when you need range queries (`lower_bound`, `upper_bound`), or when you need guaranteed bounds, otherwise default to `unordered_map`. Insertion uses bracket assignment `m[k] = v` or `m.emplace(k, v)` / `m.insert({k, v})`. The bracket form has a subtle property: if `k` is missing, it default-constructs a value and returns a reference to it. For `int` and similar arithmetic types the default is zero, which makes `m[k]++` an idiomatic counter — but it also means `m[k]` mutates the map. You cannot call it on a `const unordered_map`, and you should not call it when you are only checking whether a key exists, because it will silently add the key with a zero value and skew your data. To distinguish missing from zero, use `auto it = m.find(k); if (it != m.end()) { use(it->second); }` or, in C++20, `m.contains(k)`. Iteration yields `std::pair<const K, V>&` — the key is `const` because mutating it would break the hash invariant and corrupt the structure. Iteration order is unspecified and may change between runs or library versions; do not rely on it for reproducibility. Performance hinges on the hash function and the load factor. Standard types (`int`, `string`, pointers) have good built-in hashes shipped with the library. For a custom struct key, specialize `std::hash` or pass a hash functor as the second template argument; you also need `operator==` for equality comparison on collision. A bad hash collapses everything into one bucket and turns every operation into O(n). Rehashing happens when the load factor crosses the threshold (typically 1.0); during rehash, iterators and references are invalidated — pointers into the value type survive only because `unordered_map` stores nodes (it is node-based), but iterators do not. Memory layout is node-based, so iteration is slower than over a `vector` and cache locality is poor. For small N (a few dozen items) a sorted `vector<pair<K, V>>` with `std::lower_bound` often beats `unordered_map` in both speed and memory.",
